    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">What we do</span>
      <h2>Five termite services.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        From a $360 annual inspection through to a $20K whole-of-structure
        Mastotermes remediation. We hold the NT Pest Control licence under the
        Medicines, Poisons and Therapeutic Goods Act + AEPMA membership +
        AS 3660 Termite Inspector certification required for all of it.
      </p>

      <div class="svc-grid">
        <a class="svc-card" href="/services/pre-purchase-inspection/">
          <div class="svc-icon" aria-hidden="true">&#9728;</div>
          <h3>Pre-purchase inspection</h3>
          <p>AS 4349.3 detailed inspection with written report for property settlement. Sub-floor stumps, roof void, perimeter, garden, moisture-meter readings, Mastotermes mound scan on rural acreage. Same-day or next-day. ~$480&ndash;$680 standard residential.</p>
          <span class="svc-link">See pre-purchase inspections &rarr;</span>
        </a>

        <a class="svc-card" href="/services/annual-inspection/">
          <div class="svc-icon" aria-hidden="true">&#9783;</div>
          <h3>Annual inspection (AS 3660.2)</h3>
          <p>The mandatory yearly inspection AS 3660 expects on every Australian home. Detailed sub-floor and roof-void audit, perimeter scan, moisture readings. Written report. ~$320&ndash;$480 depending on size and whether you&rsquo;re urban Darwin or rural acreage.</p>
          <span class="svc-link">See annual inspections &rarr;</span>
        </a>

        <a class="svc-card" href="/services/chemical-soil-treatment/">
          <div class="svc-icon" aria-hidden="true">&#9783;</div>
          <h3>Chemical soil barrier</h3>
          <p>Termidor SC or Premise 200SC non-repellent termiticide injection around the perimeter. 8&ndash;10 year barrier. Mastotermes needs deeper-than-southern injection volumes because the colony footprint is wider. $2,800&ndash;$6,500 standard, more for rural reticulation.</p>
          <span class="svc-link">See chemical barriers &rarr;</span>
        </a>

        <a class="svc-card" href="/services/baiting-systems/">
          <div class="svc-icon" aria-hidden="true">&#9618;</div>
          <h3>Baiting systems</h3>
          <p>Sentricon Always Active, Exterra or Trelona ATBS in-ground stations around the perimeter. Termites take bait back to the colony, kill the queen. Excellent against Mastotermes &mdash; bait reaches diffuse colonies that miss soil barriers. Install $2,000&ndash;$3,800 + ~$420/yr.</p>
          <span class="svc-link">See baiting systems &rarr;</span>
        </a>

        <a class="svc-card" href="/services/post-construction-protection/">
          <div class="svc-icon" aria-hidden="true">&#9608;</div>
          <h3>Pre-construction barrier</h3>
          <p>For new builds and major renovations &mdash; AS 3660.1 reticulation + chemical perimeter, OR physical barrier (Kordon, HomeGuard) + perimeter chemical, OR hybrid baiting. Builder needs the Form 16 Termite Management Certificate for Form 21 occupation handover. ~$2,200&ndash;$4,200.</p>
          <span class="svc-link">See pre-construction &rarr;</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Why a Top End specialist</span>
      <h2>Three things every Darwin termite inspection should get right.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>

      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 2rem; max-width: 60rem;">
        <div>
          <h3>Mastotermes darwiniensis &mdash; the world&rsquo;s most destructive termite.</h3>
          <p>
            Australia has 350+ termite species. Three are economically destructive
            country-wide; in the Top End, the dominant species is
            <strong>Mastotermes darwiniensis</strong>, the Giant Northern Termite.
            It&rsquo;s the only surviving member of family Mastotermitidae, the most
            primitive termite lineage alive. Mastotermes colonies are
            <em>diffuse</em>, not centralised &mdash; a single colony can spread
            across 1&ndash;2 hectares with multiple satellite nests, which is why
            standard southern-Australia inspection patterns miss them. Mastotermes
            will eat timber, paper, leather, plastic, rubber, soft metals (lead
            flashing, copper insulation, sometimes aluminium fly-screen frames),
            and high-lime concrete. You don&rsquo;t inspect for Mastotermes by
            looking for one mud-tube near a sub-floor bearer &mdash; you scan the
            whole 1&ndash;2ha around the building including outbuildings, fence
            lines, garden timbers and any bushland boundary.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>High-set on stumps + monsoonal moisture = perfect storm.</h3>
          <p>
            Greater Darwin&rsquo;s older housing stock &mdash; 1960s&ndash;80s
            high-set timber on concrete or steel stumps &mdash; was designed for
            cyclone uplift, not termite resistance. Sub-floor crawl-spaces stay
            humid for 6&ndash;9 months of the year (wet season + build-up + early
            dry), softening bearers and joists. Combined with chronic ant-cap
            failure on older stumps and decades of garden mulch piled against
            stump bases, a Coptotermes or Mastotermes colony can establish in
            sub-floor undetected for years. About 18&ndash;22% of our pre-purchase
            inspections on pre-1990 high-set homes find active or recently-active
            termite evidence. Annual inspection is non-negotiable on these
            properties; many clients move to 6-monthly.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Chemical barriers expire &mdash; check when yours was last renewed.</h3>
          <p>
            Pre-1995 chemical-barrier treatments used organochlorines (chlordane,
            dieldrin) which last 40+ years but are now banned. Post-1995 treatments
            used permethrin or bifenthrin (10&ndash;15 year life). Modern
            non-repellent chemicals (Termidor SC, Premise 200SC) last 8&ndash;10
            years. A 1995 permethrin barrier is now 30 years old &mdash; expired.
            A 2015 Termidor treatment is in its last year. Look at the Termite
            Management Certificate (Form 16) installed under the meter box or in
            the electrical sub-board &mdash; if there isn&rsquo;t one, the property
            has been unprotected for some time. The NT&rsquo;s tropical climate
            shortens chemical half-life; we&rsquo;ve seen 10-year-rated barriers
            test inactive at 7&ndash;8 years on north-facing soil. We can confirm
            at inspection and quote renewal.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
